%N A115747 Numbers k such that phi(k) + sigma(k) = (5/2)*k.
%C A115747 If p = 3*2^(m-1)-1 is an odd prime then 2^m*p is in the sequence because phi(2^m*p) = 2^(m-1)*(3*2^(m-1)-2), sigma(2^m*p) = (2^(m+1)-1)*(3*2^(m-1)) so phi(2^m*p)+sigma(2^m*p) = 2^(m-1)*(3* 2^(m-1)-2)+(2^(m+1)-1)*(3*2^(m-1)) = 3*2^(2m-2)-2^m+3*2^(2m)-3*2^ (m-1) = 2^(m-1)*(3*2^(m-1)-2+3*2^(m+1)-3) = 2^(m-1)*(3*5*2^(m-1)-5) = 5/2*2^m*(3*2^(m-1)-1) = 5/2*(2^m*p).
%C A115747 a(15) > 10^13. - _Giovanni Resta_, Jul 13 2015
%e A115747 25161728 is in the sequence because phi(25161728) + sigma(25161728) = 12578816 + 50325504 = 5/2*25161728.
%t A115747 Do[If[DivisorSigma[1,n]+EulerPhi[n]==5/2*n,Print[n]],{n,200000000}]
